<h2 id="overview">Overview: Two Platforms, Two Philosophies</h2>

Both Thinkific and Teachable let you build and host online courses. They look similar on the surface -- drag-and-drop course builders, video hosting, student management, payment processing. But they're built for different primary use cases, and that shows in their feature priorities.

<p><strong>Thinkific</strong> prioritizes the learning experience. Quizzes, assignments, certificates, completion tracking, communities, and compliance features. It's built around ensuring students actually learn the material -- which is exactly what operators need for training.</p>

<p><strong>Teachable</strong> prioritizes the sales experience. Checkout optimization, upsells, order bumps, affiliate programs, and marketing tools. It's built around maximizing revenue from course sales -- which matters for creators selling to consumers.</p>

I've used Thinkific for our partner training program and evaluated Teachable as an alternative. Here's how they compare for operator use cases.

