<h2 id="course-builder">Course Builder</h2>

Both platforms have competent course builders. You can add video lessons, text, PDFs, and downloadable resources in either one. The editing experience is similar -- drag to reorder, click to edit, preview before publishing.

<p><strong>Where Thinkific pulls ahead for operators:</strong></p>

Thinkific's quiz engine lets you set minimum passing scores and gate progress -- a student can't move to Module 3 until they pass the Module 2 quiz with 80% or higher. For compliance training and safety certifications, this isn't optional. Teachable has quizzes but the gating is less granular.

Thinkific's assignment feature (Start plan and above) lets you require students to submit work that you review before they progress. For training programs where you need to verify hands-on competence -- not just video watching -- this matters.

<p><strong>Where Teachable pulls ahead:</strong></p>

Teachable's student-facing design is more polished. The course player looks better, the checkout flow converts better, and the overall aesthetic is more modern. If your students are paying customers rather than internal staff, that polish affects conversion rates.

