<p><strong>The math:</strong> Thinkific's zero transaction fees matter if you're selling courses. On Teachable's Basic plan, selling a $100 course costs you $5 per sale in transaction fees on top of the subscription. But for internal operator training where you're not charging students, transaction fees are irrelevant -- and Thinkific's free tier is significantly more useful than Teachable's (no fees vs $1 + 10%).</p>

<h2 id="training">For Operator Training: Thinkific Wins</h2>

If your primary use case is training staff, partners, franchisees, or venue teams, Thinkific is the better choice:

<ul>
  <li><strong>Free tier lets you start without risk</strong> -- unlimited students, no transaction fees, one full course</li>
  <li><strong>Quiz gating ensures comprehension</strong> -- students can't skip ahead without demonstrating knowledge</li>
  <li><strong>Certificate generation</strong> creates auditable compliance records</li>
  <li><strong>Bulk enrollment</strong> (Grow plan) lets you onboard entire teams at once</li>
  <li><strong>Communities</strong> create peer support channels that reduce your support load</li>
  <li><strong>Completion tracking</strong> shows exactly who's trained and who isn't across all locations</li>
</ul>

I built our partner training on Thinkific specifically because of quiz gating and completion tracking. When a venue manager completes training, their GoHighLevel pipeline stage updates automatically via Zapier. I can see at a glance which of my thousands of venues have fully trained staff without asking anyone.

<h2 id="selling">For Selling Courses: Teachable Wins</h2>

If your primary use case is selling courses to an external audience -- monetizing your operator expertise as a digital product -- Teachable is the better choice:

<ul>
  <li><strong>Checkout optimization</strong> -- order bumps, upsells, and coupon codes are built for conversion</li>
  <li><strong>Marketing tools</strong> -- built-in affiliate program, email marketing, and student referrals</li>
  <li><strong>Design polish</strong> -- the student experience looks and feels more premium</li>
  <li><strong>Payment flexibility</strong> -- payment plans, subscriptions, and one-time purchases with optimized checkout</li>
</ul>

The transaction fees on lower tiers are the tradeoff, but if you're generating significant course revenue, upgrading to Pro ($119/mo) eliminates them.

